(b) Want of variety in the rhythm os successive lines This is a grave delect even when not emphasized by marked pauses; and here too Vergil had shewn the better way. Take such a passage as 11 16—42. The matter is such as might have wrought mightily on a Roman poet and found its utterance in memorable words oi noble sound. But through weakness of rhythm and diction the passage is dull and commonplace. The same may be said oi a great many other passages3 and when the matter has no particular interest os its own the effect is of course worse.
